{"title_page": "North Island robin", "text_new": "{{short description|Passerine species of bird native to New Zealand's North Island}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = North Island robin\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{Cite iucn | author = BirdLife International | title = ''Petroica longipes'' | volume = 2016 | page = e.T103735022A104114188 | date = 2016 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T103735022A104114188.en }}</ref>\n| image = North Island Robin-edit.jpg\n| genus = Petroica\n| species = longipes\n| authority = [[Prosper Garnot|Garnot]], 1827\n}}\nThe '''North Island robin''' (''Petroica longipes'') is a species of [[Petroicidae|Australasian robin]] [[endemism|endemic]] to the [[North Island]] of [[New Zealand]]. It and the [[South Island robin]] (''P. australis'') of the [[South Island]] and [[Stewart Island]] were once considered conspecific (and called the \"New Zealand robin\"), but [[mitochondrial DNA]] sequences have shown that the two lineages split prior to the [[Pleistocene]], and support the classification as two different species.<ref name = \"Miller\">Miller, Hilary C. & Lambert, David M. (2006): A molecular phylogeny of New Zealand's ''Petroica'' (Aves: Petroicidae) species based on mitochondrial DNA sequences. ''Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution'' '''40'''(3): 844\u2013855.</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Juvenile NZ Robin.jpg|thumb|left|Juvenile begging for food]]\nThe [[plumage]] is dark grey-black overall, with a pale area on the belly and breast (which is smaller than that of the South Island robin), and pale streaking on the upperparts. They are [[sexual dimorphism|sexually dimorphic]], with males having darker plumage than the females and being slightly larger.<ref>Armstrong, D (2001) \"Sexing North Island robins (''Petroica australis longipes'') from morphometrics and plumage\" ''Notornis'' '''48''': 76\u201380</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe North Island robin is distributed mostly in the centre of the North Island, with small [[relict]] populations in the north and south, on Moturua Island in the [[Bay of Islands]], [[Little Barrier Island]], and [[Kapiti Island]].<ref name = \"Higgins\">Higgins, P.J. & J.M. Peter (eds) 2003. ''Handbook of Australian, New Zealand and Antarctic Birds.  Volume 6: Pardalotes to Shrike-thrushes. '' Oxford University Press, Melbourne.  {{ISBN|0-19-553762-9}}</ref> Populations have been reestablished in the [[Zealandia (wildlife sanctuary)|Zealandia  sanctuary]] in Wellington, and at [[Moehau]] on the [[Coromandel Peninsula]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.visitzealandia.com/About/Wildlife/Birds/North-Island-Robin |title=North Island robin |work=Zealandia |publisher=Karori Sanctuary Trust |accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref><ref>Department of Conservation (2006) [http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/native-animals/birds/birds-a-z/north-island-robin-toutouwai/docs-work/toutouwai-robins-return/ Wildlife welcome robin onto Moehau in the northern Coromandel]. Retrieved 21 November 2013</ref> A remnant population is also reestablishing itself in the Ohope Scenic Reserve, near [[Whakatane]]; 40 birds were translocated to the reserve from [[Mokoia Island]] to assist the population there.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mokoia\u2019s robins successfully breeding in \u014chope |url=https://www.doc.govt.nz/news/media-releases/2015/mokoias-robins-successfully-breeding-in-ohope/ |publisher=[[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] |access-date=7 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nTheir natural habitat is mostly native forest, particularly ''[[Podocarpus]]'' and southern beech (Nothofagaceae) forests, from sea level up to the tree-line.\n\n==Behaviour==\n\n[[File:North Island Robin with weta.jpg|thumb|this robin has caught a tree weta]]\n===Feeding===\n[[File:NZ North Island Robin-3.jpg|thumb|left|Standing perfectly still on a perch awaiting prey]]\nThe North Island robin, like the South Island robin, is a terrestrial feeder foraging on or near the ground (unlike the related and more arboreal [[tomtit]]). Prey items are located by perch-hunting, where an individual waits at an elevated perch until prey is spotted, or by active searching; prey is taken from the leaf-litter, low vegetation (branches and foliage) and tree trunks. Numerous [[invertebrate]] prey is taken, including [[cicada]]s, [[earthworm]]s, [[weta]]s, snails, and spiders. Fruit is also taken.<ref name = \"Higgins\"/> North Island robins cache food supplies for later when prey is plentiful, although males cache more food than females do.<ref>Burns, K.C. & Steer J (2006) \"Dominance rank influences food hoarding in New Zealand Robins ''Petroica australis''\" ''Ibis'' '''148''': 266\u2013272</ref> Both sexes will steal food from their mate's cache, and are less likely to cache food if their mate is present.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Petroicidae}}\n{{Birds of New Zealand}}\n{{Portal bar|Birds|New Zealand}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3316087}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:robin, North Island}}\n[[Category:Petroica|North Island robin]]\n[[Category:Birds of the North Island]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1827|North Island robin]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Prosper Garnot|North Island robin]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Passerine species of bird native to New Zealand's North Island}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = North Island robin\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{Cite iucn | author = BirdLife International | title = ''Petroica longipes'' | volume = 2016 | page = e.T103735022A104114188 | date = 2016 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T103735022A104114188.en }}</ref>\n| image = North Island Robin-edit.jpg\n| genus = Petroica\n| species = longipes\n| authority = [[Prosper Garnot|Garnot]], 1827\n}}\nThe '''North Island robin''' (''Petroica longipes'') is a species of [[Petroicidae|Australasian robin]] [[endemism|endemic]] to the [[North Island]] of [[New Zealand]]. It and the [[South Island robin]] (''P. australis'') of the [[South Island]] and [[Stewart Island]] were once considered conspecific (and called the \"New Zealand robin\"), but [[mitochondrial DNA]] sequences have shown that the two lineages split prior to the [[Pleistocene]], and support the classification as two different species.<ref name = \"Miller\">Miller, Hilary C. & Lambert, David M. (2006): A molecular phylogeny of New Zealand's ''Petroica'' (Aves: Petroicidae) species based on mitochondrial DNA sequences. ''Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution'' '''40'''(3): 844\u2013855.</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Juvenile NZ Robin.jpg|thumb|left|Juvenile begging for food]]\nThe [[plumage]] is dark grey-black overall, with a pale area on the belly and breast (which is smaller than that of the South Island robin), and pale streaking on the upperparts. They are [[sexual dimorphism|sexually dimorphic]], with males having darker plumage than the females and being slightly larger.<ref>Armstrong, D (2001) \"Sexing North Island robins (''Petroica australis longipes'') from morphometrics and plumage\" ''Notornis'' '''48''': 76\u201380</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe North Island robin is distributed mostly in the centre of the North Island, with small [[relict]] populations in the north and south in Moturua Island in the [[Bay of Islands]], [[Little Barrier Island]] and [[Kapiti Island]].<ref name = \"Higgins\">Higgins, P.J. & J.M. Peter (eds) 2003. ''Handbook of Australian, New Zealand and Antarctic Birds.  Volume 6: Pardalotes to Shrike-thrushes. '' Oxford University Press, Melbourne.  {{ISBN|0-19-553762-9}}</ref> Populations have been reestablished in [[Zealandia (wildlife sanctuary)|Zealandia  sanctuary]] in Wellington and [[Moehau]] in the [[Coromandel Peninsula]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.visitzealandia.com/About/Wildlife/Birds/North-Island-Robin |title=North Island robin |work=Zealandia |publisher=Karori Sanctuary Trust |accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref><ref>Department of Conservation (2006) [http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/native-animals/birds/birds-a-z/north-island-robin-toutouwai/docs-work/toutouwai-robins-return/ Wildlife welcome robin onto Moehau in the northern Coromandel]. Retrieved 21 November 2013</ref> A remnant population is also re-establishing itself in the Ohope Scenic Reserve near [[Whakatane]]; 40 birds were translocated to the reserve from [[Mokoia Island]] to assist the population there.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mokoia\u2019s robins successfully breeding in \u014chope |url=https://www.doc.govt.nz/news/media-releases/2015/mokoias-robins-successfully-breeding-in-ohope/ |publisher=[[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] |access-date=7 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nTheir natural habitat is mostly natural forest, particularly ''[[Podocarpus]]'' and southern beech (Nothofagaceae) forests, from sea level up to the tree line.\n\n==Behaviour==\n\n[[File:North Island Robin with weta.jpg|thumb|this robin has caught a tree weta]]\n===Feeding===\n[[File:NZ North Island Robin-3.jpg|thumb|left|Standing perfectly still on a perch awaiting prey]]\nThe North Island robin, like the South Island robin, is a terrestrial feeder foraging on or near the ground (unlike the related and more arboreal [[tomtit]]). Prey items are located by perch-hunting, where an individual waits at an elevated perch until prey is spotted, or by active searching; prey is taken from the leaf-litter, low vegetation (branches and foliage) and tree trunks. Numerous [[invertebrate]] prey is taken, including [[cicada]]s, [[earthworm]]s, [[weta]]s, snails, and spiders. Fruit is also taken.<ref name = \"Higgins\"/> North Island robins cache food supplies for later when prey is plentiful, although males cache more food than females do.<ref>Burns, K.C. & Steer J (2006) \"Dominance rank influences food hoarding in New Zealand Robins ''Petroica australis''\" ''Ibis'' '''148''': 266\u2013272</ref> Both sexes will steal food from their mate's cache, and are less likely to cache food if their mate is present.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Petroicidae}}\n{{Birds of New Zealand}}\n{{Portal bar|Birds|New Zealand}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3316087}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:robin, North Island}}\n[[Category:Petroica|North Island robin]]\n[[Category:Birds of the North Island]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1827|North Island robin]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Prosper Garnot|North Island robin]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDistribution and habitat:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North_Island_robin"}
{"title_page": "Cifesa", "text_new": "'''Cifesa''' is the [[acronym]] for '''Compa\u00f1\u00eda Industrial Film Espa\u00f1ola''', a noted Spanish film studio. They have released such films as ''[[Don Quixote de la Mancha (1947 film)|Don Quijote de la Mancha]]'' (1947) <ref name=\"imdb.com\">https://www.imdb.com/company/co0054607</ref> and the 1954 film version of ''[[El alcalde de Zalamea]]'', as well as being responsible for the Spanish release of some Hollywood films.<ref name=\"imdb.com\"/> Notable stars include [[Flori\u00e1n Rey]], [[Benito Perojo]], [[Imperio Argentina]], and [[Miguel Ligero (Spanish actor)|Miguel Ligero]].<ref name=\"Pavlovi\u01072008\">{{cite book| last1 = Pavlovi\u0107| first1 = Tatjana| last2 = Alvarez| first2 = Inmaculada| last3 = Blanco-Cano| first3 = Rosana| title = 100 Years of Spanish Cinema| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=wsYqAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA25| accessdate = 15 July 2012| date = 18 November 2008| publisher = John Wiley & Sons| isbn = 978-1-4051-8420-5| page = 25 }}</ref> In 1951 the studio released the historical epic ''[[Dawn of America]]'', intended as a response to the big-budget British production ''[[Christopher Columbus (1949 film)|Christopher Columbus]]'' (1949).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Film production companies of Spain]]\n[[Category:Spanish film studios]]\n\n{{film-studio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Cifesa''' is the [[acronym]] for '''Compania Industrial Film Espa\u00f1ola''', a noted Spanish film studio. They have released such films as ''[[Don Quixote de la Mancha (1947 film)|Don Quijote de la Mancha]]'' (1947) <ref name=\"imdb.com\">https://www.imdb.com/company/co0054607</ref> and the 1954 film version of ''[[El alcalde de Zalamea]]'', as well as being responsible for the Spanish release of some Hollywood films.<ref name=\"imdb.com\"/> Notable stars include [[Flori\u00e1n Rey]], [[Benito Perojo]], [[Imperio Argentina]], and [[Miguel Ligero (Spanish actor)|Miguel Ligero]].<ref name=\"Pavlovi\u01072008\">{{cite book| last1 = Pavlovi\u0107| first1 = Tatjana| last2 = Alvarez| first2 = Inmaculada| last3 = Blanco-Cano| first3 = Rosana| title = 100 Years of Spanish Cinema| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=wsYqAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA25| accessdate = 15 July 2012| date = 18 November 2008| publisher = John Wiley & Sons| isbn = 978-1-4051-8420-5| page = 25 }}</ref> In 1951 the studio released the historical epic ''[[Dawn of America]]'', intended as a response to the big-budget British production ''[[Christopher Columbus (1949 film)|Christopher Columbus]]'' (1949).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Film production companies of Spain]]\n[[Category:Spanish film studios]]\n\n{{film-studio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Xaverius", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cifesa"}
{"title_page": "Powfu", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian rapper}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Powfu\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| alias            = \n| birth_name       = Isaiah Faber<ref>https://www.starnow.com/izzifaber</ref>\n| birth_date       = \n| birth_place      = [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], Canada\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n* [[lo-fi hip hop]]\n}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Rapper|singer|songwriter}}\n| instrument       = Vocals\n| years_active     = 2018\u2013present\n| label            = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| associated_acts  = [[Beabadoobee]]\n| website          = \n}}\n'''Isaiah Faber''', known professionally as '''Powfu''', is a Canadian rapper, singer, and songwriter.\n\nHe is best known for his song \"[[Death Bed]]\", featuring Filipino-British singer [[Beabadoobee]]. The single has received over 150 million plays on Spotify and peaked at #43 on the [[Billboard Hot 100]] after amassing popularity through the video sharing app, [[TikTok]], where over 3 million videos using the song have been posted.\n\nUpon re-releasing the single commercially a year after, Powfu signed with [[Columbia Records]].\n\n==Discography==\n===Singles ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"10\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Certifications\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"|[[Canadian Hot 100|CAN]]<br><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Beabadoobee/chart-history/CAN|title=Beabadoobee Chart History (Canadian Hot 100)|website=Billboard|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"|[[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br><ref name=\"ARIA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/charts/singles-chart|title=ARIA Australian Top 50 Singles|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"|[[The Official Finnish Charts|FIN]]<br><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ifpi.fi/lista/artistit/powfu%2C+beabadoobee/death+bed+/|title=Powfu, Beabadoobee: Death Bed|website=[[Musiikkituottajat|Musiikkituottajat \u2013 IFPI Finland]]|language=fi-FI|url-status=live|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"|[[Irish Singles Chart|IRE]]<br><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://irish-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Beabadoobee|title=Discography Beabadoobee|website=irish-charts.com|url-status=live|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"|[[Dutch Single Top 100|NL]]<br><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dutchcharts.nl/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Beabadoobee|title=Discografie Beabadoobee|website=dutchcharts.nl|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"|[[VG-lista|NOR]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://topplista.no/charts/singles/2020-w12/|title=VG-lista \u2013 Topp 20 Single uke 12, 2020|publisher=[[VG-lista]]|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"|[[Official New Zealand Music Chart|NZ]]<br><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/chart/singles?chart=4841|title=NZ Top 40 Singles Chart|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|date=6 April 2020|access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"|[[Sverigetopplistan|SWE]]<br><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sverigetopplistan.se/chart/41?dspy=2020&dspp=14|title=Veckolista Singlar, vecka 14|publisher=[[Sverigetopplistan]]|access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"|[[UK Singles Chart|UK]]<br><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/57147/powfu-ft-beabadoobee/|title=POWFU FT BEABADOOBEE {{!}} full Official Chart History|website=[[Official Charts Company]]|url-status=live|access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"|[[Billboard Hot 100|US]]<br><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/beabadoobee/chart-history/HSI|title=Beabadoobee Chart History: Billboard Hot 100|website=Billboard|access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2020\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Death Bed]]\"<br>{{small|(featuring [[Beabadoobee]])}}\n| 20 || 6 || 9 || 13<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/irish-singles-chart/20200327/ie7501|title=Official Irish Singles Chart Top 50|publisher=Official Charts Company|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> || 45 || 14 || 7 || 15 || 8 || 33\n|\n* [[Australian Recording Industry Association|ARIA]]: Gold<ref name=\"ARIA\"/>\n| {{N/a|Non-album single}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{musician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian rapper}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Powfu\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| alias            = \n| birth_name       = Isaiah Faber<ref>https://www.starnow.com/izzifaber</ref>\n| birth_date       = \n| birth_place      = [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], Canada\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n* [[lo-fi hip hop]]\n}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Rapper|singer|songwriter}}\n| instrument       = Vocals\n| years_active     = 2018\u2013present\n| label            = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| associated_acts  = [[Beabadoobee]]\n| website          = \n}}\n'''Isaiah Faber''', known professionally as '''Powfu''', is a Canadian rapper, singer, and songwriter.\n\nHe is best known for his song \"[[Death Bed]]\", featuring Filipino-British singer [[Beabadoobee]]. The single has received over 150 million plays on Spotify and peaked at #43 on the [[Billboard Ho