 - Smith scored one of the goals in the 6-0 win.\n\n===Transfers===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n==== Players in ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%;width:98%; text-align:left\"\n|-\n!Player\n!From\n!Date\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} Ally Johnstone\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Clydebank F.C.|Clydebank]] \n| 16 Jul 1951\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Jimmy Scott (footballer, born 1927)|Jimmy Scott]]\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Armadale Thistle F.C.|Armadale Thistle]] \n| 16 Jul 1951\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Hugh Shaw (footballer, born 1929)|Hugh Shaw]]\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Duntocher Hibernian F.C.|Duntocher Hibs]] \n| 16 Jul 1951\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} Jimmy Forbes\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] (loan) \n| 14 Sep 1951\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} Eddie Beaton\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] (loan) \n| 18 Sep 1951\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} Peter Murphy\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Clydebank F.C.|Clydebank]] \n| 3 Oct 1951\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} Gerry McCaffrey\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} Campsie BW \n| 1 Mar 1952\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n==== Players out ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%;width:98%; text-align:left\"\n|-\n!Player\n!To\n!Date\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} Willie Johnstone\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} Freed\n| 30 Apr 1952\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} Ally Johnstone\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} Freed\n| 30 Apr 1952\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} Willie McLaren\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} Freed\n| 30 Apr 1952\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} John Sharp\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} Freed\n| 30 Apr 1952\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n<small>Source:<ref>{{cite book | last = Litster | first = John | title = Record of Pre-War Scottish League Players | publisher = PM Publications | location = Norwich}}</ref></small>\n\n==Reserve team==\nDumbarton played a reserve team in Division C (South West) and finished 12th out of 16, recording 11 wins and 4 draws from 30 matches.  Note that in addition to the reserve sides of the bigger Division A teams in South and West Scotland, the first teams of East Stirlingshire (relegated from Division B three seasons previously) and Stranraer also competed in this league.\n\nIn the Second XI Cup, Dumbarton lost in the second round to Dundee United.\n\nFinally in the Reserve League Cup, Dumbarton could only manage a win and a draw from their 6 sectional matches and failed to progress to the knock-out stages.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{1951\u201352 in Scottish football}}\n{{Dumbarton F.C. seasons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dumbarton}}\n[[Category:Dumbarton F.C. seasons]]\n[[Category:Scottish football clubs 1951\u201352 season]]\n[[Category:1951\u201352 in Scottish football]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox football club season\n| club               = [[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]]\n| season             = 1951\u20131952\n| manager            = William Irvine\n| chairman           = \n| stadium            = Boghead Park, Dumbarton\n| league             = [[1951\u201352 Scottish Football League|Scottish League B Division]]\n| league result      = 10th\n| cup1               = [[1951\u201352 Scottish Cup|Scottish Cup]]\n| cup1 result        = Third Round\n| cup2               = [[1951\u201352 Scottish League Cup|Scottish League Cup]]\n| cup2 result        = Prelims\n| cup3               = [[B Division Supplementary Cup|Supplementary Cup]]\n| cup3 result        = Second Round\n| league topscorer   = Jimmy Scott (14)\n| season topscorer   = Jimmy Scott (20)\n| highest attendance = \n| lowest attendance  = \n| average attendance = \n| pattern_la1        = _black_hoops\n| pattern_b1         = _goldhoops\n| pattern_ra1        = _black_hoops\n| pattern_so1        = _goldtop\n| leftarm1           = ffc100\n| body1              = 000000\n| rightarm1          = ffc100\n| shorts1            = ffffff\n| socks1             = 000000\n| prevseason         = [[1950\u201351 Dumbarton F.C. season|1950\u201351]]\n| nextseason         = [[1952\u201353 Dumbarton F.C. season|1952\u201353]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1951\u201352''' season was the 68th [[Football in Scotland|Scottish football]] season in which [[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]] competed at national level, entering the [[Scottish Football League]], the [[Scottish Cup]], the [[Scottish League Cup]], the [[B Division Supplementary Cup|Supplementary Cup]], and the Festival of Britain Quaich.  In additon dumbarton competed in the [[Stirlingshire Cup]].\n\n==Scottish League==\n{{Main|1951\u201352 Scottish Football League}}\nAnother slow start to the league campaign, with only a single win from 9 attempts, meant that Dumbarton were never seen as challengers for the title but improving performances during the season resulted in a mid-table 10th-place finish with 28 points, 16 behind champions Clyde.\n\n{{football box collapsible\n|result  =L\n|date =8 September 1951\n|round =[[1951-52 Scottish Football League|Division B]]\n|score = 0-1<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/dumbarton/game.php?gameid=36787 |title=Dumbarton 0 - 1 Falkirk, Scottish League (08/09/1951)|publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sonsarchive.com/matchdetails.php?id=1610 |title=Dumbarton 0 - 1 Falkirk, Saturday, September 8th 1951 |publisher=The Sons Archive |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n|team1 =[[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]]\n|team2 =[[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]]\n|goals1 =\n|goals2 =Brown {{goal|}}\n|stadium =[[Boghead Park]]\n|attendance =4,000\n|referee =W Brown\n|motm =\n}}\n{{football box collapsible\n|result  =L\n|date =15 September 1951\n|round =[[1951-52 Scottish Football League|Division B]]\n|score = 2-1<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/dumbarton/game.php?gameid=22544 |title=Kilmarnock 2 - 1 Dumbarton, Scottish League (15/09/1951)|publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sonsarchive.com/matchdetails.php?id=1611 |title=Kilmarnock 2 - 1 Dumbarton, Saturday, September 15th 1951 |publisher=The So